<h2><span class="ez-toc-section" id="Flowers_to_Plant_in_Spring"></span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Flowers to Plant in Spring</span><span class="ez-toc-section-end"></span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Even if your garden is already filled with colorful flowers, you’ll need to plan ahead if you want plants to keep blooming into the summer. Plant these flowers in the spring so you can enjoy a supply of colorful blooms well into the fall. You can plant some of these flowers from seed, but others work best as transplants, so make sure to read up on each flower before you add it to your garden.</span></p>
<ul>
<li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Sunflower</span></li>
<li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Gladiolus</span></li>
<li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Marigold</span></li>
<li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Sweet alyssum</span></li>
<li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Columbine</span></li>
<li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Black-eyed Susan</span></li>
<li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Dianthus</span></li>
<li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Lavender</span></li>
<li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Zinnia</span></li>
</ul>
<h2><span class="ez-toc-section" id="Best_Spring_Flowers"></span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Best Spring Flowers</span><span class="ez-toc-section-end"></span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">If you’re looking for flowers that bloom in March, April, and May, check out this list. All of the following spring flowers brighten up your garden, and some of them also work well as cut flowers.</span></p>
<h3><span class="ez-toc-section" id="1_Viola"></span><span style="font-weight: 400;">1. Viola</span><span class="ez-toc-section-end"></span></h3>
<p><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-14325" src="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/pansy-3401542_1280-824x550.jpg" alt="White and violet violas growing outside" width="824" height="550" srcset="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/pansy-3401542_1280-824x550.jpg 824w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/pansy-3401542_1280-400x267.jpg 400w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/pansy-3401542_1280-768x512.jpg 768w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/pansy-3401542_1280-1080x721.jpg 1080w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/pansy-3401542_1280.jpg 1280w" sizes="(max-width: 824px) 100vw, 824px" /></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Violas look like versions of pansies, with many colorful blooms on each plant. While violas don’t handle hot temperatures very well, they shine in cool spring weather. They can even survive light frosts!</span></p>
<p><b>USDA Grow Zone:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> 3–8</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Sun:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Full sun to part shade</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Soil:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Rich and well-draining with a slightly acidic pH</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Why We Love This Flower:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Violas are </span><a href="https://bouqs.com/blog/edible-flowers/"><span style="font-weight: 400;">edible flowers</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> with a subtle floral taste – try adding the flowers to salads or using them to decorate cakes!</span></p>
<h3><span class="ez-toc-section" id="2_Lobelia"></span><span style="font-weight: 400;">2. Lobelia</span><span class="ez-toc-section-end"></span></h3>
<p><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-14540" src="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/nikki-son-ekhXJ2WR9Mc-unsplash-min-825x550.jpg" alt="Purple lobelia flowers growing outside" width="825" height="550" srcset="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/nikki-son-ekhXJ2WR9Mc-unsplash-min-825x550.jpg 825w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/nikki-son-ekhXJ2WR9Mc-unsplash-min-400x267.jpg 400w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/nikki-son-ekhXJ2WR9Mc-unsplash-min-768x512.jpg 768w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/nikki-son-ekhXJ2WR9Mc-unsplash-min-1080x720.jpg 1080w" sizes="(max-width: 825px) 100vw, 825px" /></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">While lobelia is actually a perennial, its tender nature means many people treat it as an annual. The plants are low-growing with a bit of a trailing form, making them a good choice for window boxes, rock gardens, edging plants, and more!</span></p>
<p><b>USDA Grow Zone:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> 3–11</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Sun: </b><span style="font-weight: 400;">Part shade to full sun</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Soil:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Moist and well-draining</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Why We Love This Flower:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Deer and other critters tend to leave these plants alone.</span></p>
<h3><span class="ez-toc-section" id="3_Petunia"></span><span style="font-weight: 400;">3. Petunia</span><span class="ez-toc-section-end"></span></h3>
<p><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-13864" src="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/petunia-177388_1280-733x550.jpg" alt="Pink petunia flowers blooming outside" width="733" height="550" srcset="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/petunia-177388_1280-733x550.jpg 733w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/petunia-177388_1280-400x300.jpg 400w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/petunia-177388_1280-768x576.jpg 768w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/petunia-177388_1280-1080x810.jpg 1080w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/petunia-177388_1280.jpg 1280w" sizes="(max-width: 733px) 100vw, 733px" /></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">As fast-growing plants with a seemingly never-ending supply of blooms, petunias are a beloved garden flower. While they’re treated as annuals in most places, they can be grown as tender perennials in zones 10 and 11.</span></p>
<p><b>USDA Grow Zone:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> 3–11</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Sun:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Full sun</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Soil:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Moist and well-draining</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Why We Love This Flower:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Petunias start blooming in spring but continue flowering throughout the summer!</span></p>
<h3><span class="ez-toc-section" id="4_Snapdragon"></span><span style="font-weight: 400;">4. Snapdragon</span><span class="ez-toc-section-end"></span></h3>
<p><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-14180" src="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/snapdragons-g26f134b3b_1280-825x550.jpg" alt="" width="825" height="550" srcset="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/snapdragons-g26f134b3b_1280-825x550.jpg 825w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/snapdragons-g26f134b3b_1280-400x267.jpg 400w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/snapdragons-g26f134b3b_1280-768x512.jpg 768w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/snapdragons-g26f134b3b_1280-1080x720.jpg 1080w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/snapdragons-g26f134b3b_1280.jpg 1280w" sizes="(max-width: 825px) 100vw, 825px" /></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">With tall spikes of colorful blooms, snapdragons are a delightful addition to spring gardens and planter boxes. They thrive in the cool weather found during the spring and fall.</span></p>
<p><b>USDA Grow Zone:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> 2–11</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Sun:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Part shade to full sun</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Soil:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Moist and well-draining</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Why We Love This Flower:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Snapdragons add height to mixed bouquets and can last for about a week.</span></p>
<h3><span class="ez-toc-section" id="5_Ranunculus"></span><span style="font-weight: 400;">5. Ranunculus</span><span class="ez-toc-section-end"></span></h3>
<p><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-14412" src="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/11/ranunkeln-5056684_1280-825x550.jpg" alt="" width="825" height="550" srcset="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/11/ranunkeln-5056684_1280-825x550.jpg 825w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/11/ranunkeln-5056684_1280-400x267.jpg 400w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/11/ranunkeln-5056684_1280-768x512.jpg 768w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/11/ranunkeln-5056684_1280-1080x720.jpg 1080w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/11/ranunkeln-5056684_1280.jpg 1280w" sizes="(max-width: 825px) 100vw, 825px" /></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">While Ranunculus is the name for the buttercup genus, people use this term to refer to specific plants bred for beautiful cut flowers. While you can grow ranunculus yourself, you’ll need to start the plants from corms. However, flower farmers often grow these flowers, so look for them in bouquets.</span></p>
<p><b>USDA Grow Zone:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> 8–11</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Sun:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Full sun</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Soil:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Rich and well-drained</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Why We Love This Flower:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Ranunculus has exquisite layers of delicate petals, making them a show-stopping flower.</span></p>
<h3><span class="ez-toc-section" id="6_Sweet_Alyssum"></span><span style="font-weight: 400;">6. Sweet Alyssum</span><span class="ez-toc-section-end"></span></h3>
<p><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-14184" src="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/sweet-alyssum-g869e34501_1280-828x550.jpg" alt="White sweet alyssum growing outside" width="828" height="550" srcset="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/sweet-alyssum-g869e34501_1280-828x550.jpg 828w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/sweet-alyssum-g869e34501_1280-400x266.jpg 400w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/sweet-alyssum-g869e34501_1280-768x510.jpg 768w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/sweet-alyssum-g869e34501_1280-1080x717.jpg 1080w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/sweet-alyssum-g869e34501_1280.jpg 1280w" sizes="(max-width: 828px) 100vw, 828px" /></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">These plants produce many clusters of tiny flowers with a sweet fragrance. Since they have so many blooms, they look great tucked into rock gardens, window boxes, and garden beds.</span></p>
<p><b>USDA Grow Zone:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> 2–11</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Sun:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Part shade to full sun</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Soil:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Moist and well-draining</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Why We Love This Flower:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Sweet alyssum flowers attract many beneficial insects, including parasitic wasps and native bees.</span></p>
<h3><span class="ez-toc-section" id="7_Stock"></span><span style="font-weight: 400;">7. Stock</span><span class="ez-toc-section-end"></span></h3>
<div id="attachment_13857" style="width: 810px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><img class="size-full wp-image-13857" src="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/stock-flowers.jpeg" alt="Stock flowers growing outside" width="800" height="533" srcset="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/stock-flowers.jpeg 800w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/stock-flowers-400x267.jpeg 400w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/stock-flowers-768x512.jpeg 768w" sizes="(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /><p class="wp-caption-text">Credit: Wiki Commons: https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Matthiola_incana_Vintage_Burgundy_0zz.jpg</p></div>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">With a sweet yet slightly spicy scent, long vase life, and beautiful flowers, stock is a must-have spring flower. The blooms come in a wide range of colors, including pink, white, purple, and yellow. While the majority of people grow stock as an annual, if you live in zones 7–10 you can grow it as a tender perennial.</span></p>
<p><b>USDA Grow Zone:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> 4–10</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Sun:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Part shade to full sun</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Soil:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Rich and well-draining</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Why We Love This Flower:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Although you may not know it, stock flowers are closely related to brassicas like broccoli and cabbage!</span></p>
<h3><span class="ez-toc-section" id="8_Hellebore"></span><span style="font-weight: 400;">8. Hellebore</span><span class="ez-toc-section-end"></span></h3>
<p><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-14394" src="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/christmas-rose-4015895_1280-825x550.jpg" alt="Close-up of hellebore (christmas rose) flower outside" width="825" height="550" srcset="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/christmas-rose-4015895_1280-825x550.jpg 825w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/christmas-rose-4015895_1280-400x267.jpg 400w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/christmas-rose-4015895_1280-768x512.jpg 768w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/christmas-rose-4015895_1280-1080x720.jpg 1080w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/christmas-rose-4015895_1280.jpg 1280w" sizes="(max-width: 825px) 100vw, 825px" /></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The hellebore is one of the first flowers to make an appearance in the spring, often blooming as snow still blankets the ground. Due to its early spring timing and delicate petals, it’s also known as the lenten rose.</span></p>
<p><b>USDA Grow Zone:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> 3–9</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Sun:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Partial shade to shade</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Soil:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Well-draining yet moist</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Why We Love This Flower:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Not only are hellebore flowers beautiful in the garden, but they also have attractive leaves that provide interest year-round.</span></p>
<h3><span class="ez-toc-section" id="9_Primrose"></span><span style="font-weight: 400;">9. Primrose</span><span class="ez-toc-section-end"></span></h3>
<p><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-14481" src="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/primroses-4783108_1280-633x550.jpg" alt="Pink-white primrose flowers growing outside" width="633" height="550" srcset="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/primroses-4783108_1280-633x550.jpg 633w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/primroses-4783108_1280-400x348.jpg 400w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/primroses-4783108_1280-768x668.jpg 768w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/primroses-4783108_1280-1080x939.jpg 1080w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/primroses-4783108_1280.jpg 1280w" sizes="(max-width: 633px) 100vw, 633px" /></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Primroses are a huge group of plants with over 500 species in the family. Their flowers range from purple to yellow to pink, so you’re likely to find an option that suits your tastes. Although some varieties may bloom during the summer, the vast majority produce flowers in the spring.</span></p>
<p><b>USDA Grow Zone:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> 2–8</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Sun:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Partial shade or shade</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Soil:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Well-draining, rich, and moist</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Why We Love This Flower:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Primroses need very little care, making them an easy way to add a pop of color to shady areas.</span></p>
<h3><span class="ez-toc-section" id="10_Adonis"></span><span style="font-weight: 400;">10. Adonis</span><span class="ez-toc-section-end"></span></h3>
<p><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-14541" src="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/hiroshi-tsubono-37oVzXDs_bs-unsplash-828x550.jpg" alt="Close-up of yellow adonis flower." width="828" height="550" srcset="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/hiroshi-tsubono-37oVzXDs_bs-unsplash-828x550.jpg 828w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/hiroshi-tsubono-37oVzXDs_bs-unsplash-400x266.jpg 400w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/hiroshi-tsubono-37oVzXDs_bs-unsplash-768x510.jpg 768w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/hiroshi-tsubono-37oVzXDs_bs-unsplash-1080x718.jpg 1080w" sizes="(max-width: 828px) 100vw, 828px" /></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">A member of the buttercup family, adonis flowers are one of the first flowers to bloom each spring. They’re also known as pheasant’s eye and false hellebore.</span></p>
<p><b>USDA Grow Zone:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> 3–7</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Sun:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Part shade to full sun</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Soil:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Moist and well-draining</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Why We Love This Flower:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Along with beautiful flowers, these plants also produce lacy foliage.</span></p>
<h3><span class="ez-toc-section" id="11_Lily_of_the_Valley"></span><span style="font-weight: 400;">11. Lily of the Valley</span><span class="ez-toc-section-end"></span></h3>
<p><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-11506" src="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/lily-of-the-valley-shade-garden.jpg" alt="lily of the valley for shade garden" width="600" height="399" srcset="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/lily-of-the-valley-shade-garden.jpg 600w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/lily-of-the-valley-shade-garden-400x266.jpg 400w" sizes="(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px" /></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Don’t let the name deceive you, these plants are actually more closely related to asparagus. Regardless, these short plants produce elegant white flowers. The plants tend to spread, so they’re a great choice if you’re looking for a flowering ground cover.</span></p>
<p><b>USDA Grow Zone:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> 3–8</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Sun:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Partial shade to full sun</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Soil:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Rich and well-draining</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Why We Love This Flower:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> While lily of the valley flowers may be small, they produce an intoxicating fragrance that’s reminiscent of floral perfumes.</span></p>
<h3><span class="ez-toc-section" id="12_Virginia_Bluebells"></span><span style="font-weight: 400;">12. Virginia Bluebells</span><span class="ez-toc-section-end"></span></h3>
<p><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-14542" src="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/sara-cottle-mxuz-AbTW9g-unsplash-825x550.jpg" alt="Light blue Virginia bluebells growing outside" width="825" height="550" srcset="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/sara-cottle-mxuz-AbTW9g-unsplash-825x550.jpg 825w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/sara-cottle-mxuz-AbTW9g-unsplash-400x267.jpg 400w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/sara-cottle-mxuz-AbTW9g-unsplash-768x512.jpg 768w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/sara-cottle-mxuz-AbTW9g-unsplash-1080x720.jpg 1080w" sizes="(max-width: 825px) 100vw, 825px" /></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Often found beside rivers and streams, Virginia bluebells brighten shady, moist gardens with their periwinkle blooms. Although the majority of open blooms are blue, the flower buds are often pale pink.</span></p>
<p><b>USDA Grow Zone:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> 3–8</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Sun:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Partial shade to shade</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Soil:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Rich and moist</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Why We Love This Flower:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Humans aren’t the only ones who love these flowers—bees, butterflies, and hummingbirds visit to drink the flower’s nectar.</span></p>
<h3><span class="ez-toc-section" id="13_Trillium"></span><span style="font-weight: 400;">13. Trillium</span><span class="ez-toc-section-end"></span></h3>
<p><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-14543" src="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/karl-damus-gQFvR4YcmJQ-unsplash-min-808x550.jpg" alt="White trillium flower growing outside" width="808" height="550" srcset="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/karl-damus-gQFvR4YcmJQ-unsplash-min-808x550.jpg 808w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/karl-damus-gQFvR4YcmJQ-unsplash-min-400x272.jpg 400w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/karl-damus-gQFvR4YcmJQ-unsplash-min-768x523.jpg 768w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/karl-damus-gQFvR4YcmJQ-unsplash-min-1080x736.jpg 1080w" sizes="(max-width: 808px) 100vw, 808px" /></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Named for their trio of petals and sepals, trillium flowers emerge in the spring in rich, moist soils. Depending on the species, the flowers can be white, yellow, red, or another hue. Some species have flowers with skyward-facing petals while others produce flowers that nod to the ground below the plant’s leaves.</span></p>
<p><b>USDA Grow Zone:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> 4–9</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Sun:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Part shade to full shade</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Soil:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Rich, moist, and well-draining</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Why We Love This Flower:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> The plants emerge year after year in the spring, making them some of the best spring flowers for long-term color.</span></p>
<h3><span class="ez-toc-section" id="14_Tulip"></span><span style="font-weight: 400;">14. Tulip</span><span class="ez-toc-section-end"></span></h3>
<p><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-10353" src="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/tulips-827x550.jpg" alt="Purple yellow and white tulips in a field highlight by sunshine" width="827" height="550" srcset="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/tulips-827x550.jpg 827w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/tulips-400x266.jpg 400w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/tulips-768x511.jpg 768w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/tulips-1080x718.jpg 1080w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/tulips-50x33.jpg 50w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/tulips.jpg 1200w" sizes="(max-width: 827px) 100vw, 827px" /></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Whether you enjoy tulips in your garden or in a bouquet, it’s hard to imagine spring without them. Since these flowers grow from bulbs, you’ll need to plan ahead. However, the foresight is worth it. And if you’re looking for an amazing tulip display, visit spring flower fields near you!</span></p>
<p><b>USDA Grow Zone:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> 3–8</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Sun:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Full sun</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Soil:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Rich and well-draining</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Why We Love This Flower:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Tulips come in all sorts of colors and varieties – check out fringed tulips and parrot tulips if you’re looking to mix things up.</span></p>
<h3><span class="ez-toc-section" id="15_Daffodil"></span><span style="font-weight: 400;">15. Daffodil</span><span class="ez-toc-section-end"></span></h3>
<p><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-14486" src="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/shutterstock_1706808361-min-825x550.jpg" alt="White and yellow daffodils growing outside" width="825" height="550" srcset="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/shutterstock_1706808361-min-825x550.jpg 825w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/shutterstock_1706808361-min-400x267.jpg 400w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/shutterstock_1706808361-min-768x512.jpg 768w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/shutterstock_1706808361-min-1080x720.jpg 1080w" sizes="(max-width: 825px) 100vw, 825px" /></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Plant daffodil bulbs in the fall, and you’ll be rewarded with cheerful yellow flowers the following spring. While the bright blooms work well in bouquets, they also produce a toxin that will cause some other types of flowers to wilt. If you want to spice things up, look for fancy daffodils with multiple layers of petals.</span></p>
<p><b>USDA Grow Zone:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> 4–8</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Sun:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Part shade to full sun</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Soil:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Rich and well-draining</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Why We Love This Flower:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Critters like moles and deer typically leave daffodil bulbs alone, so they’re a great choice if you’re sharing your yard with wildlife.</span></p>
<h3><span class="ez-toc-section" id="16_Crocus"></span><span style="font-weight: 400;">16. Crocus</span><span class="ez-toc-section-end"></span></h3>
<p><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-14317" src="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/flowers-190866_1280-733x550.jpg" alt="Field of purple crocus flowers" width="733" height="550" srcset="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/flowers-190866_1280-733x550.jpg 733w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/flowers-190866_1280-400x300.jpg 400w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/flowers-190866_1280-768x576.jpg 768w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/flowers-190866_1280-1080x810.jpg 1080w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/flowers-190866_1280.jpg 1280w" sizes="(max-width: 733px) 100vw, 733px" /></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Crocuses are one of the first bulb flowers to bloom each spring, often sneaking out from ground covered with snow or frost. Crocuses are grown from corms, not bulbs, but they act similarly to many other bulb flowers.</span></p>
<p><b>USDA Grow Zone:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> 3–8</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Sun:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Part shade to full sun</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Soil:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Well-draining</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Why We Love This Flower:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Since crocuses are short flowers—maxing out at six inches—they work well in front of other plants.</span></p>
<h3><span class="ez-toc-section" id="17_Hyacinth"></span><span style="font-weight: 400;">17. Hyacinth</span><span class="ez-toc-section-end"></span></h3>
<p><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-13435" src="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/hyacinth-gbfb6701d2_1280-825x550.jpg" alt="Pink hyacinth blooming outdoors" width="825" height="550" srcset="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/hyacinth-gbfb6701d2_1280-825x550.jpg 825w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/hyacinth-gbfb6701d2_1280-400x267.jpg 400w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/hyacinth-gbfb6701d2_1280-768x512.jpg 768w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/hyacinth-gbfb6701d2_1280-1080x720.jpg 1080w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/hyacinth-gbfb6701d2_1280.jpg 1280w" sizes="(max-width: 825px) 100vw, 825px" /></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Not only are hyacinths gorgeous, but they also produce one of the most unmistakable floral scents. Their blue, pink, and white flowers fit in nicely with </span><a href="https://bouqs.com/blog/lesser-known-spring-holidays/"><span style="font-weight: 400;">holidays to celebrate in spring</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;">.</span></p>
<p><b>USDA Grow Zone:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> 4–8</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Sun:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Part shade to full sun</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Soil:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Moist and well-draining</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Why We Love This Flower:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> You can plant hyacinth bulbs almost anywhere, including in the garden, in a container, and in a water-filled vase.</span></p>
<h3><span class="ez-toc-section" id="18_Snowdrop"></span><span style="font-weight: 400;">18. Snowdrop</span><span class="ez-toc-section-end"></span></h3>
<p><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-14405" src="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/snowdrop-4865866_1280-824x550.jpg" alt="" width="824" height="550" srcset="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/snowdrop-4865866_1280-824x550.jpg 824w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/snowdrop-4865866_1280-400x267.jpg 400w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/snowdrop-4865866_1280-768x512.jpg 768w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/snowdrop-4865866_1280-1080x721.jpg 1080w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/snowdrop-4865866_1280.jpg 1280w" sizes="(max-width: 824px) 100vw, 824px" /></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">As their name suggests, snowdrops bloom in early spring when snow may still be around. While their white flowers are beautiful, be aware they’re toxic to humans and pets.</span></p>
<p><b>USDA Grow Zone:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> 3–7</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Sun:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Partial shade to full sun</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Soil:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Loose and well-draining</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Why We Love This Flower:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> The bulbs naturally multiply, so you can dig them up and move them to other areas…or share them with friends.</span></p>
<h3><span class="ez-toc-section" id="19_Forsythia"></span><span style="font-weight: 400;">19. Forsythia</span><span class="ez-toc-section-end"></span></h3>
<p><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-14544" src="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/aubrey-odom-MLLh714yJpI-unsplash-822x550.jpg" alt="Forsythia flowers growing outside" width="822" height="550" srcset="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/aubrey-odom-MLLh714yJpI-unsplash-822x550.jpg 822w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/aubrey-odom-MLLh714yJpI-unsplash-400x268.jpg 400w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/aubrey-odom-MLLh714yJpI-unsplash-768x514.jpg 768w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/aubrey-odom-MLLh714yJpI-unsplash-1080x723.jpg 1080w" sizes="(max-width: 822px) 100vw, 822px" /></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">With bright yellow flowers and a low-maintenance growth habit, forsythia is one of the most popular flowering shrubs. They flower before they produce leaves, which is a bit unusual.</span></p>
<p><b>USDA Grow Zone:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> 5–8</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Sun:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Part shade to full sun</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Soil:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Well-draining</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Why We Love This Flower:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Forsythia can last about a week as a cut flower.</span></p>
<h3><span class="ez-toc-section" id="20_Lilac"></span><span style="font-weight: 400;">20. Lilac</span><span class="ez-toc-section-end"></span></h3>
<p><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-13950" src="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/lilac-5061139_1280-824x550.jpg" alt="Violet lilac tree blooming outside" width="824" height="550" srcset="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/lilac-5061139_1280-824x550.jpg 824w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/lilac-5061139_1280-400x267.jpg 400w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/lilac-5061139_1280-768x512.jpg 768w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/lilac-5061139_1280-1080x721.jpg 1080w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/lilac-5061139_1280.jpg 1280w" sizes="(max-width: 824px) 100vw, 824px" /></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Lilacs produce clusters of flowers that draw in both humans and butterflies. Make sure to plant them in full sun if you want lots of flowers!</span></p>
<p><b>USDA Grow Zone:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> 3–7</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Sun:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Full sun</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Soil:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Well-draining</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Why We Love This Flower:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Whether you enjoy these flowers in the garden or as part of a bouquet, you’ll fall in love with their sweet fragrance.</span></p>
<h3><span class="ez-toc-section" id="21_Japanese_Pieris"></span><span style="font-weight: 400;">21. Japanese Pieris</span><span class="ez-toc-section-end"></span></h3>
<div id="attachment_14545" style="width: 614px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><img class="size-large wp-image-14545" src="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/Pieris_japonica-604x550.jpeg" alt="Japanese Pieris flowers growing outside" width="604" height="550" srcset="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/Pieris_japonica-604x550.jpeg 604w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/Pieris_japonica-400x364.jpeg 400w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/Pieris_japonica.jpeg 640w" sizes="(max-width: 604px) 100vw, 604px" /><p class="wp-caption-text">Credit: https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Pieris_forest_flame_A.jpg</p></div>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Also known as the lily of the valley shrub, this plant produces many clusters of small, bell-shaped flowers. Unlike true lilies of the valley, these flowers don’t have a strong fragrance.</span></p>
<p><b>USDA Grow Zone:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> 5–8</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Sun:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Part shade to full sun</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Soil:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Moist, well-draining, and acidic</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Why We Love This Flower:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Along with delicate flowers, Japanese Pieris also produces evergreen foliage, which often emerges in shades of red.</span></p>
<h3><span class="ez-toc-section" id="22_Witch_Hazel"></span><span style="font-weight: 400;">22. Witch Hazel</span><span class="ez-toc-section-end"></span></h3>
<p><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-14322" src="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/witch-hazel-3137717_1280-825x550.jpg" alt="Branch growing yellow witch hazel flowers" width="825" height="550" srcset="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/witch-hazel-3137717_1280-825x550.jpg 825w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/witch-hazel-3137717_1280-400x267.jpg 400w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/witch-hazel-3137717_1280-768x512.jpg 768w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/witch-hazel-3137717_1280-1080x720.jpg 1080w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/witch-hazel-3137717_1280.jpg 1280w" sizes="(max-width: 825px) 100vw, 825px" /></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">While you may have heard of witch hazel in skin care products, this plant also produces yellow flowers. Sometimes witch hazel blooms in the late fall or winter, but it may also bloom in the early spring.</span></p>
<p><b>USDA Grow Zone:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> 3–9</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Sun:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Part shade to full sun</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Soil:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Moist and well-draining</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Why We Love This Flower:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Both the species and weather impact when witch hazel flowers, so it’s always a bit of a surprise.</span></p>
<h3><span class="ez-toc-section" id="23_Azalea"></span><span style="font-weight: 400;">23. Azalea</span><span class="ez-toc-section-end"></span></h3>
<p><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-14395" src="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/azalea-4044121_1280-824x550.jpg" alt="Close-up of pink azalea flower growing outside" width="824" height="550" srcset="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/azalea-4044121_1280-824x550.jpg 824w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/azalea-4044121_1280-400x267.jpg 400w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/azalea-4044121_1280-768x512.jpg 768w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/azalea-4044121_1280-1080x721.jpg 1080w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/azalea-4044121_1280.jpg 1280w" sizes="(max-width: 824px) 100vw, 824px" /></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Whether you have an azalea planted in your garden or enjoy seeing hundreds of native azaleas in the wild, it’s hard to imagine spring without these gorgeous shrubs. Thanks to breeding efforts, more than 10,000 cultivars now exist!</span></p>
<p><b>USDA Grow Zone:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> 3–9</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Sun:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Part shade to full sun</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Soil:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Acidic and well-draining</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Why We Love This Flower:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Azaleas come in a wide variety of sizes and colors, so you can find one you love.</span></p>
<h3><span class="ez-toc-section" id="24_Bleeding_Heart"></span><span style="font-weight: 400;">24. Bleeding Heart</span><span class="ez-toc-section-end"></span></h3>
<p><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-13904" src="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/nature-3218674_1280-825x550.jpg" alt="Bleeding heart flower growing outside" width="825" height="550" srcset="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/nature-3218674_1280-825x550.jpg 825w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/nature-3218674_1280-400x267.jpg 400w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/nature-3218674_1280-768x512.jpg 768w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/nature-3218674_1280-1080x720.jpg 1080w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/nature-3218674_1280.jpg 1280w" sizes="(max-width: 825px) 100vw, 825px" /></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The bleeding heart is a vegetative plant that grows to resemble a small shrub. It produces dazzling heart-shaped flowers each spring.</span></p>
<p><b>USDA Grow Zone:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> 2–9</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Sun:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Part shade to full shade</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Soil:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Moist and high in organic matter</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Why We Love This Flower:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> The plants are easy to care for and thrive in shady conditions.</span></p>
<h3><span class="ez-toc-section" id="25_Peonies"></span><span style="font-weight: 400;">25. Peonies</span><span class="ez-toc-section-end"></span></h3>
<p><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-14278" src="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/peony-287062_1280-733x550.jpg" alt="Pink peony blooming outside" width="733" height="550" srcset="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/peony-287062_1280-733x550.jpg 733w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/peony-287062_1280-400x300.jpg 400w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/peony-287062_1280-768x576.jpg 768w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/peony-287062_1280-1080x810.jpg 1080w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/peony-287062_1280.jpg 1280w" sizes="(max-width: 733px) 100vw, 733px" /></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Not only do peonies brighten up your garden, but they look beautiful in arrangements. Try cutting the flowers when they’re just starting to bloom so you can watch the petals emerge over time.</span></p>
<p><b>USDA Grow Zone:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> 3–9</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Sun:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Partial shade to full sun</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Soil:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Well-draining</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Why We Love This Flower:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Although peonies start blooming in the spring, their blooms last into the summer.</span></p>
<h3><span class="ez-toc-section" id="26_Camellia"></span><span style="font-weight: 400;">26. Camellia</span><span class="ez-toc-section-end"></span></h3>
<p><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-14194" src="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/camellia-g5d47e67c4_1280-792x550.jpg" alt="Pink camellia flower blooming outside" width="792" height="550" srcset="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/camellia-g5d47e67c4_1280-792x550.jpg 792w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/camellia-g5d47e67c4_1280-400x278.jpg 400w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/camellia-g5d47e67c4_1280-768x533.jpg 768w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/camellia-g5d47e67c4_1280-1080x750.jpg 1080w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/camellia-g5d47e67c4_1280.jpg 1280w" sizes="(max-width: 792px) 100vw, 792px" /></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">If you live in a warmer region, consider adding the evergreen camellia to your garden. These plants are gorgeous year-round, but their stunning flowers make them a real showpiece in the garden. With hundreds of varieties of camellia to choose from, there’s no doubt you can find one of these plants you’ll love.</span></p>
<p><b>USDA Grow Zone:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> 7–9</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Sun:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Part shade</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Soil:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Well-draining and slightly acidic</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Why We Love This Flower:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Camellias bloom in the winter or early spring when landscapes are otherwise barren.</span></p>
<h3><span class="ez-toc-section" id="27_Sweet_Pea"></span><span style="font-weight: 400;">27. Sweet Pea</span><span class="ez-toc-section-end"></span></h3>
<p><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-14517" src="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/shutterstock_1851429481-min-940x451.jpg" alt="" width="940" height="451" srcset="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/shutterstock_1851429481-min-940x451.jpg 940w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/shutterstock_1851429481-min-400x192.jpg 400w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/shutterstock_1851429481-min-768x368.jpg 768w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/shutterstock_1851429481-min-1080x518.jpg 1080w" sizes="(max-width: 940px) 100vw, 940px" /></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">If you’re looking for a spring flower that’s not only beautiful but also fills your garden with a sweet, intoxicating fragrance, you can’t go wrong with the sweet pea. Plus, they’re also one of the </span><a href="https://bouqs.com/blog/aprils-birth-month-flower/"><span style="font-weight: 400;">birth flowers for April</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;">!</span></p>
<p><b>USDA Grow Zone:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> 3–8</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Sun:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Full sun</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Soil:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Well-draining and moist</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Why We Love This Flower:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Sweet peas have delicate yet strong tendrils that help them climb up garden structures like fences and arbors.</span></p>
<h3><span class="ez-toc-section" id="28_Anemone"></span><span style="font-weight: 400;">28. Anemone</span><span class="ez-toc-section-end"></span></h3>
<p><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-14411" src="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/11/flowers-215565_1280-825x550.jpg" alt="" width="825" height="550" srcset="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/11/flowers-215565_1280-825x550.jpg 825w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/11/flowers-215565_1280-400x267.jpg 400w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/11/flowers-215565_1280-768x512.jpg 768w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/11/flowers-215565_1280-1080x720.jpg 1080w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/11/flowers-215565_1280.jpg 1280w" sizes="(max-width: 825px) 100vw, 825px" /></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">After spending a long winter tucked in the ground, anemone plants muster up their energy in the early spring to send out beautiful poppy-like flowers. They come in colors including white, red, pink, and purple.</span></p>
<p><b>USDA Grow Zone:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> 3–7</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Sun:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Full sun</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Soil:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Well-draining and moist</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Why We Love This Flower:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> These early spring flowers are some of the first to bloom in the spring.</span></p>
<h3><span class="ez-toc-section" id="29_Foxglove"></span><span style="font-weight: 400;">29. Foxglove</span><span class="ez-toc-section-end"></span></h3>
<p><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-13910" src="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/thimble-2377079_1280-914x550.jpg" alt="Violet foxglove flower blooming outside" width="914" height="550" srcset="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/thimble-2377079_1280-914x550.jpg 914w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/thimble-2377079_1280-400x241.jpg 400w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/thimble-2377079_1280-768x462.jpg 768w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/thimble-2377079_1280-1080x650.jpg 1080w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/thimble-2377079_1280.jpg 1280w" sizes="(max-width: 914px) 100vw, 914px" /></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">When spring arrives, foxglove plants produce tall flower stalks covered with bell-shaped blooms. Since the plants grow as biennials or short-lived perennials, don’t expect them to produce flowers in their first year.</span></p>
<p><b>USDA Grow Zone:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> 4–9</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Sun:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Full sun</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Soil:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Well-draining, rich, and moist</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Why We Love This Flower:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Foxglove flower stalks grow multiple feet tall, making them a great focal flower for arrangements. </span></p>
<h3><span class="ez-toc-section" id="30_Delphinium"></span><span style="font-weight: 400;">30. Delphinium</span><span class="ez-toc-section-end"></span></h3>
<p><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-13716" src="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/delphinium-850359_1280-733x550.jpg" alt="" width="733" height="550" srcset="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/delphinium-850359_1280-733x550.jpg 733w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/delphinium-850359_1280-400x300.jpg 400w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/delphinium-850359_1280-768x576.jpg 768w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/delphinium-850359_1280-1080x810.jpg 1080w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/delphinium-850359_1280.jpg 1280w" sizes="(max-width: 733px) 100vw, 733px" /></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">A stunning genus of flowering plants, delphinium sends up tall flower stalks with delicate, open flowers. Although many people consider delphinium summer flowers, planting them in a protected culture like a high tunnel allows you to enjoy the blooms by mid-spring.</span></p>
<p><b>USDA Grow Zone:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> 3–7</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Sun:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Full sun</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Soil:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Rich and well-draining</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Why We Love This Flower:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Delphinium comes in a wide range of colors and heights, so you can find a variety that fits your garden well.</span></p>
<h3><span class="ez-toc-section" id="31_Trout_Lily"></span><span style="font-weight: 400;">31. Trout Lily</span><span class="ez-toc-section-end"></span></h3>
<div id="attachment_14546" style="width: 650px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><img class="size-full wp-image-14546" src="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/trout-lily.jpg" alt="Close-up of white trout lily flowers" width="640" height="407" srcset="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/trout-lily.jpg 640w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/trout-lily-400x254.jpg 400w" sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px" /><p class="wp-caption-text">Credit: https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Erythronium_tuolumnense_White_Beauty._Locatie,_Tuinreservaat_Jonkervallei_01.jpg</p></div>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">If you live in the eastern or midwestern United States, you may have seen cute yellow trout lily flowers blanketing forest slopes and streambanks. These spring ephemerals emerge for just a few weeks, making them a true spring treat.</span></p>
<p><b>USDA Grow Zone:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> 3–9</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Sun:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Part shade or shade</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Soil:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Rich, moist, and well-draining</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Why We Love This Flower:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Trout lily plants often grow in groups and turn entire hillsides yellow.</span></p>
<h3><span class="ez-toc-section" id="32_Bloodroot"></span><span style="font-weight: 400;">32. Bloodroot</span><span class="ez-toc-section-end"></span></h3>
<p><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-14547" src="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/katherine-mangum-WwI3EPj0HVc-unsplash-889x550.jpg" alt="Close-up of white bloodroot flower" width="889" height="550" srcset="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/katherine-mangum-WwI3EPj0HVc-unsplash-889x550.jpg 889w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/katherine-mangum-WwI3EPj0HVc-unsplash-400x248.jpg 400w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/katherine-mangum-WwI3EPj0HVc-unsplash-768x475.jpg 768w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/katherine-mangum-WwI3EPj0HVc-unsplash-1080x668.jpg 1080w" sizes="(max-width: 889px) 100vw, 889px" /></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">A native wildflower in much of the eastern United States, bloodroot produces delicate white flowers in the early spring. The plant&#8217;s large, light green leaves almost resemble hands that seem to gently curl around each flower stem.</span></p>
<p><b>USDA Grow Zone:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> 3–9</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Sun:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Part shade or shade</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Soil:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Rich, moist, and well-draining</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Why We Love This Flower:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Bloodroot gets its name from its bright red roots, which indigenous people used as dye.</span></p>
<h3><span class="ez-toc-section" id="33_Bluebonnet"></span><span style="font-weight: 400;">33. Bluebonnet</span><span class="ez-toc-section-end"></span></h3>
<p><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-13962" src="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/bluebonnets-2433508_1280-825x550.jpg" alt="Blue bonnet flowers growing outside" width="825" height="550" srcset="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/bluebonnets-2433508_1280-825x550.jpg 825w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/bluebonnets-2433508_1280-400x267.jpg 400w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/bluebonnets-2433508_1280-768x512.jpg 768w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/bluebonnets-2433508_1280-1080x720.jpg 1080w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/bluebonnets-2433508_1280.jpg 1280w" sizes="(max-width: 825px) 100vw, 825px" /></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Known for brightening landscapes of the South and Southwest, bluebonnets emerge sometime in the spring. The individual flowers, which some people say resemble bonnets, sit on a long, thin flower stalk. Although the flowers are beautiful, their toxic nature means you should be careful if you have curious pets or children at home.</span></p>
<p><b>USDA Grow Zone:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> 4–8</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Sun:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Full sun</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Soil:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Well-draining</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Why We Love This Flower:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> The blue color found in many bluebonnet species provides a nice contrast to red, orange, and yellow blooms.</span></p>
<h3><span class="ez-toc-section" id="34_Siberian_Squill"></span><span style="font-weight: 400;">34. Siberian Squill</span><span class="ez-toc-section-end"></span></h3>
<p><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-14548" src="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/alksndra-URma7hfxBLA-unsplash-828x550.jpg" alt="Close-up of blue siberian squill flower" width="828" height="550" srcset="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/alksndra-URma7hfxBLA-unsplash-828x550.jpg 828w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/alksndra-URma7hfxBLA-unsplash-400x266.jpg 400w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/alksndra-URma7hfxBLA-unsplash-768x510.jpg 768w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/alksndra-URma7hfxBLA-unsplash-1080x718.jpg 1080w" sizes="(max-width: 828px) 100vw, 828px" /></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">An extremely cold-hardy plant, the Siberian squill sends out tiny blue flowers in early spring. The plants remain less than eight inches tall, but their clump-forming nature means they often form carpets where they are planted.</span></p>
<p><b>USDA Grow Zone:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> 2–8</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Sun: </b><span style="font-weight: 400;">Full sun or part shade</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Soil:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Well-draining</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Why We Love This Flower:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> The flowers can survive frost and snow, making them an excellent addition to cold areas.\</span></p>
<h3><span class="ez-toc-section" id="35_Creeping_Phlox"></span><span style="font-weight: 400;">35. Creeping Phlox</span><span class="ez-toc-section-end"></span></h3>
<p><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-14549" src="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/steph-jsRepEiI9lw-unsplash-min-825x550.jpg" alt="Violet creeping phlox growing outside" width="825" height="550" srcset="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/steph-jsRepEiI9lw-unsplash-min-825x550.jpg 825w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/steph-jsRepEiI9lw-unsplash-min-400x267.jpg 400w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/steph-jsRepEiI9lw-unsplash-min-768x512.jpg 768w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/steph-jsRepEiI9lw-unsplash-min-1080x720.jpg 1080w" sizes="(max-width: 825px) 100vw, 825px" /></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">A hardy groundcover with short, straight leaves that resemble pine leaves, creeping phlox fits well in rock gardens, borders, and window boxes.  The plants become covered with five-petal flowers in the mid to late spring and continue blooming for multiple weeks.</span></p>
<p><b>USDA Grow Zone:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> 5–9</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Sun: </b><span style="font-weight: 400;">Full sun or part shade</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Soil:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Well-draining</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Why We Love This Flower:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Since it’s native to North America, creeping phlox is an excellent groundcover choice.</span></p>
<h3><span class="ez-toc-section" id="36_Grape_Hyacinth"></span><span style="font-weight: 400;">36. Grape Hyacinth</span><span class="ez-toc-section-end"></span></h3>
<p><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-14550" src="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/haley-parson-PZwpG5EDySE-unsplash-825x550.jpg" alt="Close-up of grape hyacinth flowers growing outside" width="825" height="550" srcset="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/haley-parson-PZwpG5EDySE-unsplash-825x550.jpg 825w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/haley-parson-PZwpG5EDySE-unsplash-400x267.jpg 400w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/haley-parson-PZwpG5EDySE-unsplash-768x512.jpg 768w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/haley-parson-PZwpG5EDySE-unsplash-1080x720.jpg 1080w" sizes="(max-width: 825px) 100vw, 825px" /></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">While some people think they’re just miniature versions of the larger hyacinth, grape hyacinths are actually a </span><a href="https://hort.extension.wisc.edu/articles/grape-hyacinth-muscari-armeniacum"><span style="font-weight: 400;">completely different species</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;">. You can’t grow them in pots indoors, but these plants make excellent additions to outdoor gardens.</span></p>
<p><b>USDA Grow Zone:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> 3–9</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Sun: </b><span style="font-weight: 400;">Full sun</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Soil:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Well-draining</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Why We Love This Flower:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> The clusters of tiny, purple flowers are some of the cutest spring flowers available.</span></p>
<h3><span class="ez-toc-section" id="37_Winter_Jasmine"></span><span style="font-weight: 400;">37. Winter Jasmine</span><span class="ez-toc-section-end"></span></h3>
<p><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-14313" src="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/winter-jasmine-2693682_1280-825x550.jpg" alt="Winter jasmine flowers on a branch" width="825" height="550" srcset="https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/winter-jasmine-2693682_1280-825x550.jpg 825w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/winter-jasmine-2693682_1280-400x267.jpg 400w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/winter-jasmine-2693682_1280-768x512.jpg 768w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/winter-jasmine-2693682_1280-1080x720.jpg 1080w, https://bouqs.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/winter-jasmine-2693682_1280.jpg 1280w" sizes="(max-width: 825px) 100vw, 825px" /></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The flowering shrubs begin flowering in the winter and continue to send out bright yellow blooms into the early spring. The plants have a weeping form, so they look beautiful cascading over retaining walls or down banks.</span></p>
<p><b>USDA Grow Zone:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> 6–10</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Sun: </b><span style="font-weight: 400;">Full sun or part shade</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Soil:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Well-draining</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><br />
</span><b>Why We Love This Flower:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> The flowers send color into the world at a time when most plants are dormant, making them some of the best early spring flowers.</span></p>
<h2><span class="ez-toc-section" id="Order_Flowers_for_Spring"></span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Order Flowers for Spring</span><span class="ez-toc-section-end"></span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">With so many beautiful flowers available in the spring, it’s a great time of year to order flowers. Whether you’d like to pick out a bouquet for a loved one’s birthday or brighten up your home with seasonal blooms, we’ve got you covered.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">And don’t forget about Mother’s Day! We’ve put together a great collection of </span><a href="https://bouqs.com/flowers/mothers-day"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Mother’s Day flowers</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> for every type of mom. So head on over, pick out some of your favorites, and let your mom, grandmother, and every other lady in your life let them know how much you appreciate them.</span></p>
